04204nam a22006975i 9780691224732DE-B159720220110023848.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220110t20222021nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2021010078  a97806912247327 a10.1515/97806912247322doi  a(DE-B1597)585659  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aPA3621b.H58 2021 4aPA3621b.H69 2021 7aPHI0020002bisacsh04a88022300aHow to Be a Farmer :bAn Ancient Guide to Life on the Land. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2022] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAncient Wisdom for Modern Readers0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA delightful anthology of classical Greek and Roman writings celebrating country living—ranging from a philosophy of compost to hymns to the gods of agricultureWhether you farm or garden, live in the country or long to move there, or simply enjoy an occasional rural retreat, you will be delighted by this cornucopia of writings about living and working on the land, harvested from the fertile fields of ancient Greek and Roman literature. An inspiring antidote to the digital age, How to Be a Farmer evokes the beauty and bounty of nature with a rich mixture of philosophy, practical advice, history, and humor. Together, these timeless reflections on what the Greeks called boukolika and the Romans res rusticae provide an entertaining and enlightening guide to a more meaningful and sustainable way of life.In fresh translations by classicist and farmer M. D. Usher, with the original texts on facing pages, Hesiod praises the dignity of labor; Plato describes the rustic simplicity of his ideal republic; Varro dedicates a farming manual to his wife, Fundania (“Mrs. Farmer”); and Vergil idealizes farmers as residents of the Golden Age. In other selections, Horace extols the joys of simple living at his cherished country farm; Pliny the Elder explains why all culture stems from agriculture; Columella praises donkeys and tells how to choose a ram or a dog; Musonius Rufus argues that farming is the best livelihood for a philosopher; and there is much more.Proof that farming is ultimately a state of mind we should all cultivate, How to Be a Farmer will charm anyone who loves nature or its fruits.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 10. Jan 2022) 0aAgriculture, AncientzGreecexLiterary collections. 0aAgriculture, AncientzRomexLiterary collections. 0aClassical literaturevTranslations into English. 0aCountry lifezGreecexLiterary collections. 0aCountry lifezRomexLiterary collections. 0aFarm lifezGreecevLiterary collections. 0aFarm lifezRomevLiterary collections. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh1 aUsher, M. D.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073912140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691224732423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691224732/original  a978-3-11-073912-1  Princeton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK